The head of Nigeria Competitiveness Project (NICOP) supported by the German Cooperation, cofunded by European Union EU, Mrs Ana Vinambres has said that the non governmental organisation (NGO) has so far supported 27,000 men and women across the country with a view to assist them grow their trades as well as make them to stand on their feet. Vinambres made the disclosure on Wednesday in Kano during the peer learning workshop for self-financing communities (SFC) held in Kano. The NICOP head said the sum of €11 million had been earmarked by EU to further advance the support extended by her group on its various on-going interventions  in Nigeria. “ We are in Kano to train farmers, artisans to boost their businesses and to support leather garments, tomatoes farmers increase  their added value chains by increasing the quality of their products and to help them to access new markets abroad, and have access to finance and investments.” She revealed that it is the concerned of NICOP to also support women beneficiaries have internal savings machanisms and improved their financial displine as well as  work towards setting up savings and loans groups, improved the way they are keeping their trading history so that they can access soft loans from  internal sources and  commercial banks. Mrs Vinambres stated further that NICOP initiative had started yielding positive results through empowering farmers, MSMES,  artisans, to generate more income and employments to the people . On his part, the director of cooperatives  and representative of the state government at the event, Alhaji Misbahu  Sani, applauded the efforts of NICOP and far reaching initiatives  in organising such an interactive session aimed at enlightening participants on how to do business professionally instead of  going about it traditionally. He appealed to the  participants to strictly work in agreement with  they have been taught  to improve quality and productivity .